AB  - I develop a search and matching model where agents form subjective wage expectations under the framework of Internal Rationality. Departing from rational expectations, workers and firms forecast wages using a perceived law of motion and update beliefs gradually over time. This mechanism amplifies labor market volatility, and replicates the low correlation between productivity and tightness observed in U.S. data—without imposing wage rigidities. Using survey data, I formally reject the rational expectations hypothesis. Estimated via the Method of Simulated Moments, the model matches key empirical moments and offers a novel microfoundation for belief-driven labor market dynamics.
