AB  - We propose a mechanism through which the rising market concentration causes the flattening of the Phillips curve. By extending the New Keynesian model using Homothetic Single Aggregator (HSA) demand systems, we show that a higher entry cost reduces the number of firms, which raises the markup rate and lowers the pass-through rate, thereby structurally flattening the Phillips curve. Additionally, an endogenous entry creates cost-push shocks through strategic complementarity, biasing empirical estimates. These two reasons, one structural and one observational, together can go a long way toward understanding the flattening of the Phillips curve.
